\begin{center}
But not always gaussian-like variables!
\end{center}

## But...

In Psychology, variables do not always satisfy the properties of the Gaussian distribution. For example:

- Reaction times
- Percentages or proportions (e.g., task accuracy)
- Counts
- Likert scales
- ...

